# Deployment Guide

This file describes how to deploy Vkorni safely without breaking production.

Important:
- Push to `main` triggers the GitHub Actions deploy workflow.
- Push to any other branch does not deploy.
- Docs-only or test-only changes must never be pushed to `main`.

## Current Production Model

The current production setup uses:
- GHCR images:
  - `ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-backend:latest`
  - `ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-frontend:latest`
- server path: `/opt/vkorni`
- production compose file: `docker-compose.prod.yml`
- auto deploy trigger: push to `main`

## Safe Rules

1. Never push unfinished work to `main`.
2. Never mix local dev compose and production compose on the server.
3. Keep `/opt/vkorni/.env` on the server correct before any deploy.
4. Frontend and backend must point to the right production URLs.
5. If you only changed backend, do not restart frontend unless needed.
6. If you only changed frontend, do not restart backend unless needed.

## Server Prerequisites

The server must already contain:
- `/opt/vkorni/docker-compose.prod.yml`
- `/opt/vkorni/.env`
- Docker and Docker Compose plugin
- access to GHCR

Important environment values on the server:
- `VKORNI_API_KEY`
- `VKORNI_NODE_ID`
- `VKORNI_USER_ID`
- `DEEPSEEK_KEY`
- `BACKEND_PUBLIC_URL`
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE`
- `JWT_SECRET`
- `REDIS_URL`

## Standard Full Deploy Through GitHub Actions

Use this when both frontend and backend are ready.

### Local steps

```bash
git switch main
git pull origin main
git merge <your-working-branch>
git push origin main
```

### What happens automatically

The workflow in `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`:
- builds backend image
- builds frontend image
- pushes both to GHCR
- SSHes into the server
- runs:

```bash
cd /opt/vkorni
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml pull
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d
docker image prune -f
```

## Direct Backend-Only Deploy

Use this when only backend code changed and you do not want to touch frontend.

### 1. Build and push only backend image

Run locally:

```bash
docker login ghcr.io
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 -t ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-backend:latest ./backend --push
```

### 2. Restart only backend services on the server

Run on the server:

```bash
cd /opt/vkorni
docker login ghcr.io
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml pull backend worker
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d backend worker
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps
```

### 3. Verify backend

Run on the server:

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 backend
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 worker
```

Check externally:
- backend health or docs endpoint
- one manual export
- one small bulk export

## Direct Frontend-Only Deploy

Use this when only frontend code changed.

### 1. Build and push only frontend image

Run locally:

```bash
docker login ghcr.io
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 --build-arg NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE=<production-backend-url> -t ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-frontend:latest ./frontend --push
```

Important:
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE` is baked into the frontend image at build time.
- If this value is wrong, the UI will point to the wrong backend.

### 2. Restart only frontend on the server

Run on the server:

```bash
cd /opt/vkorni
docker login ghcr.io
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml pull frontend
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d frontend
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps
```

### 3. Verify frontend

Run on the server:

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 frontend
```

Then check in browser:
- login page
- biography generation page
- export button flow

## Direct Full Deploy Without GitHub Actions

Use this only if you intentionally want manual control.

### 1. Build and push both images

```bash
docker login ghcr.io
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 -t ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-backend:latest ./backend --push
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 --build-arg NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE=<production-backend-url> -t ghcr.io/lakyn80/vkorni-frontend:latest ./frontend --push
```

### 2. Pull and restart on the server

```bash
cd /opt/vkorni
docker login ghcr.io
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml pull
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps
```

## Post-Deploy Checks

Always check all of these:

1. Containers are running:

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps
```

2. Logs do not show obvious startup failures:

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 backend
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 worker
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs --tail=200 frontend
```

3. Frontend opens correctly.
4. Backend responds correctly.
5. One single export works.
6. One bulk export works.

## Bulk Export Safety Notes

The export system is now more resilient than before:
- each profile exports in its own job
- each item has persisted attempts
- retries happen automatically
- stalled jobs can be resumed by a watchdog

Still, these are not magic guarantees. Bulk export can still be affected by:
- `vkorni.com` API downtime
- Redis outage
- server outage
- wrong server `.env`

## What Not To Do

- Do not push docs or experiments to `main`.
- Do not run `docker-compose.yml` on the production server.
- Do not redeploy frontend with a wrong `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE`.
- Do not edit `/opt/vkorni/.env` blindly without checking production URLs and secrets.
- Do not restart everything if only one service changed.

## Recommended Workflow For Normal Work

1. Work on a feature branch.
2. Test locally.
3. Push the branch.
4. Review the diff.
5. Merge to `main` only when you actually want production deploy.
6. Watch GitHub Actions.
7. Verify production after deploy.

## Current Limitation

The deployment currently uses mutable `latest` tags. That is convenient, but rollback is weaker than it should be.

The safer future improvement would be:
- build versioned tags per commit
- deploy pinned image tags
- keep a documented rollback command per release
